        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Explain why it is impossible to draw a direct common tangent when one circle lies entirely inside the other. What happens to the formula <m>L = \sqrt{d^2 - (R-r)^2}</m> in this case?
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-exer5-circle-inside">
                    <caption>
                        When <m>d \lt R - r</m>, circle <m>B</m> lies entirely inside circle <m>A</m>
                        and no direct common tangent exists.
                    </caption>
                    <image width="40%">
                        <shortdescription>
                            A large circle centred at A contains a smaller circle centred at B entirely
                            within it. A short dashed segment connects the two centres and is labelled d.
                        </shortdescription>
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}
                            % Outer circle A: center (0,0), radius 2.
                            % Inner circle B: center (0.5,0), radius 0.7.
                            % d = 0.5 &lt; R - r = 1.3, so B is inside A.
                            \tkzDefPoints{0/0/A, 0.5/0/B}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](A,2) \tkzGetPoint{cA}
                            \tkzDefCircle[R](B,0.7) \tkzGetPoint{cB}
                            \tkzDrawCircle[thick](A,cA)
                            \tkzDrawCircle[thick](B,cB)
                            \tkzDrawSegment[dashed](A,B)
                            \tkzDrawPoints(A,B)
                            \tkzLabelPoint[below left](A){$A$}
                            \tkzLabelPoint[below right](B){$B$}
                            \tkzLabelSegment[above,font=\small](A,B){$d$}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    When one circle lies inside the other, <m>d \lt R - r</m> (the distance between the centres is less than the difference of the radii). This means <m>d^2 - (R - r)^2 \lt 0</m>, so there is no real value of <m>L</m>. Geometrically, no straight line can be tangent to both circles while keeping both circles on the same side, because the inner circle always lies inside the outer one regardless of the direction of the line.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

